# Project standards and post-task checks

## Conventions (all new code)

- **Translations / i18n**: Translations must come from the backend (API), not hardcoded. Use language APIs, UI strings endpoints, and translation tables. Do not add new user-facing strings in the frontend without a backend source (e.g. i18n/languages, product_translations, taxonomy_translations).
- **APIs: use code/slug, not DB ID**: Prefer stable identifiers: language **code** (e.g. `en`, `ar`), taxonomy **slug**, brand **slug**, product **slug**. Avoid exposing or requiring auto-generated DB IDs in API contracts where a code/slug exists. Cart uses `product_slug`; product URLs are slug-based.
- **Consistency**: Match existing patterns (customer-api, admin-api, customer-web, admin-web, shop). Reuse existing helpers, schemas, and naming.
- **Architecture docs**: When changes impact the architecture (new services, ports, DB, APIs, or deployment), update [ARCHITECTURE.md](ecommerce-platform/ARCHITECTURE.md) so the overview table and “Running” sections stay accurate.
- **README and launch instructions**: Keep README files up to date with accurate steps to launch each app. The root [README.md](ecommerce-platform/README.md) must list all apps and how to run them (Quick start); each app directory (e.g. `customer-api/`, `admin-web/`) must have its own README with setup and run instructions, including any dependencies (e.g. "Start Customer API first") and required environment variables (e.g. API base URL with `/v1`). When run steps or ports change, update the affected README(s).
- **New apps**: When a new app (backend or frontend) is added to the repo, create an app-specific README in that app's folder (setup, run, env vars, and how it fits in the stack) and update the root [README.md](ecommerce-platform/README.md) (repository structure table, Quick start section, Environment variables, and Docs links).
- **Frontend design**: When making frontend changes (customer-web, admin-web, or shop UI), take inspiration from [design_template.html](ecommerce-platform/design_template.html) for layout, tokens, and patterns so the app stays aligned with the design system.
- **Loading and transitions**: Use skeleton for known layouts (product grid, PDP, admin tables); use spinner for full-page or inline actions. Follow design_template transition patterns (active:scale, duration-200/500, transition-colors). See [DESIGN_TEMPLATE.md](ecommerce-platform/DESIGN_TEMPLATE.md) “Loading and transitions.”
- **Design tokens**: Colors, spacing, radius, and typography values are defined only in the single source (`packages/design-tokens`). When adding or changing any design token, update that package (e.g. `tokens.json` and run `npm run tokens:build` to regenerate `theme.css`); do not define or hardcode token values in customer-web, admin-web, or shop. Each app may use tokens differently to achieve platform-appropriate UI (desktop web, mobile web, native app).

